Project 2: Exploring The Movie Database (TMDb)¶

Every year, thousands of movies get released but only a percentage of those become successful. The aim of this work is to analyze determining factors affecting movie profitability and commercial success. The paper is structured as follows. The first section will focus on investigating problems in a dataset and wrangling the data into a format to facilitate my analysis. The second section analyze the cleaned dataset and presents the results of my statistical analysis.

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

The main objective of this project is to analyze a dataset containing information about 10,000 movies from 1960 to 2015, collected from The Movie Database (TMDb) and including all films details such as the production cost, the revenue generated, rating information, actors and directors, etc. This work also tries to find answers to the questions below:

1- What kinds of properties are associated with most and less successful movies?

  • Which Movie had the highest or lowest profit?
  • Which year the movie industry** made the highest profit?
  • Which Month the movie industry made the highest profit?
  • Do popular movies get higher profit?
  • What were the most or least expensive movies?
  • What is the statistical relationship between budget and profit?
  • Do movies with highest budget get highest rating?
  • Which Movie had the highest or lowest revenue?
  • Is there any statistical relationship between revenue and profit/ revenue and budget?
  • What is the movie length most liked by the audience?
  • Which movie was high or less rated?
  • Do high rated movies get higher profit?

2- What are the Top 10 movies according to different features ? in particular :

  • Profit
  • Budget
  • Revenue
  • Popularity

    • 3- Which genres are most popular and profitable overall and overtime?

    • Which genres are more profitable overall?
    • Which genres are more profitable from year to year?
    • Which genres are more popular overall?
    • What is the evolution of the genres according to popularity from year to year?

    4- What are top 10 Casts, Directors and production companies ?

    Before answering to this question, let's take a look more deeply at our dataset.

    * Just according to our selected sample. In this present work, We will not talk about the global movie industry because we dont have all the database*.

    Exploratory Data Analysis¶

    Now that the dataframe is relatively clean, we are ready to explore and analyze the dataset of 3805 movies by answering to the questions already asked.

    Question 1: What kinds of properties are associated with most and less successful movies?¶

    To answer to this question, i will first calculate the financial benefit realized by each movie, by substracting the budget adjusted(accounting for inflation overtime) from the revenue adjusted. We say that there is a profit when revenue generated from a movie exceeds the expenses, costs, and taxes involved in sustaining the activity in question and vice versa for losses.

    Calculate Movies profit or loss¶

    In [27]:
    # calculate profit/ loss(losses when there are negative values) of each movie, by substracting the budget_adj from the revenue_adj of each movie
df['profit']=df['revenue_adj']-df['budget_adj']

    Create a function to extract the min and the max values¶

    So as to facilitate the answer to some questions, i will create a function that willextract the min and the max simultaneously, by using the idxmin()/idxmax() function to get the row label of the minimum/maximum value.

    In [28]:
    # Create a minmax function by using idxmin()/idxmax() function to get the row label of the minimum/maximum value.

def min_max(x):
    # calculate maximum value
    highest = df[x].idxmax()
    highest_details = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[highest])
    
    # calculate minimum value
    lowest = df[x].idxmin()
    lowest_details = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[lowest])  
    
    print('Movie which has highest '+x+' : ', df['original_title'][highest])
    print('Movie which has lowest '+x+' : ', df['original_title'][lowest])
    
    return pd.concat([highest_details, lowest_details], axis=1)

    Which month the movie industry made the highest profit?¶

    In [31]:
    releasedate_index = df.set_index('release_date')

# extract month from the release data index
groupby_index = releasedate_index.groupby([(releasedate_index.index.month)])

# Monthly data 
profit_permonth = groupby_index['profit'].sum()
profit_permonth = pd.DataFrame(profit_permonth)

#plot our data
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(10,8)}, style="whitegrid")

profit_permonth_bar = sns.barplot(x = profit_permonth.index, y = profit_permonth['profit'], data = profit_permonth)

profit_permonth_bar.axes.set_title('Profits gained by movies per months', color="r", fontsize = 18)

month_list = ['January', 'February', 'March', 'April', 'May', 'June', 'July', 'August', 'September', 'October', 'November', 'December']

#rotate the x-axis text 
profit_permonth_bar.set_xticklabels(month_list, rotation = 90, size = 14);

    We can say that june and december are the months when movies have gained the highest profits. These findings show the effect of holidays and festivities on the movie profitability.

    In [54]:
    #So as to facilitate the answer to some questions, i will create a function that will count value in descending order
def extract_data(x):
    all_data = df[x].str.cat(sep = '|')
    all_data = pd.Series(all_data.split('|'))
    
#count value in descending order
    return all_data.value_counts(ascending = False)

    Conclusions¶

    Throughout this data analysis, I found that:

    • 'Star Wars' 'Avatar', and 'Titanic' are the most profitable movies, while the top movies based on revenue gained are 'Avatar', 'Star Wars' and Titanic'. Even though these films are top 3 in term of money earned, but according to popularity it's not the same thing and they are not even in the top 5.
    • We can say that June and December are the months when movies have gained the highest profits. These findings show the effect of holidays and festivities on the movie profitability.
    • In term of correlation, i found that there is a very high and positive correlation between profit and revenue. So, companies that have larger revenues could have higher profits. Also, there is a positive and significative correlation between revenue and budget. It means that there is a good possibility that movies with higher expenses result in better revenues. To dig even deeper, causality tests should be carried out. In the other hand, there is a weak statistical relationship between the profit and the movie rating and no relationship between the budget and the runtime.
    • The top 5 dominant movie genres all over these years (1960 - 2015) are Drama, Comedy, Thriller, Action and Adventure. But this finding doesnt mean that they are the most profitable genres (the top 5 profitable are Animation, Adventure, Family, Fantasy, Science Fiction) and the most popular (Adventure, Science fiction, Fantasy, animation, action). When I dig a little deeper, I find that these genres according to profit and popularity varie quite a lot from year to year and have known a significant uptrend in recent years.
    • Finally, searching for the top actors we found Robert De Niro, Bruce Willis and Samuel L. Jackson, the top directors: Steven Spielberg Clint Eastwood, Ridley Scott and the top production companies: Universal Pictures, Warner Bros and Paramount Pictures.

    Limitations...

    This is just an attempt to analyze a small sample of movie. The film industry has thousands and thousands more. Unfortunately, there were so much missing data, that I couldnt do this analysis to a very large sample. So these findings may differ if the sample were larger.
